ğŸ§  What is an Array?

An array is a special variable that can hold multiple values under a single name.
You can access each value using an index number or a key name.

ğŸ› ï¸ Creating an Array

You can create arrays using the array() function or the short array syntax [].

Example 1 â€” Using array()
$cars = array("Volvo", "BMW", "Toyota");

Example 2 â€” Using Short Array Syntax

(Line breaks are allowed)

$cars = [
  "Volvo",
  "BMW",
  "Toyota"
];

ğŸ¯ Accessing Array Items

To access an array item, refer to its index number.

Example
$cars = array("Volvo", "BMW", "Toyota");
echo $cars[2]; // Outputs: Toyota

ğŸ”¹ Indexed Arrays (Numeric Keys)
Example
<?php
/* ------- Indexed Array Example ---------- */
$colors = array('red', 'yellow', 'blue', 'green');

echo $colors[0] . "<br>"; // red

// 2nd way
$colors = ['red', 'yellow', 'blue', 'green'];

// Display array using print_r()
echo "<pre>";
print_r($colors);
echo "</pre>";

// 3rd way â€” assigning values individually
$colors[0] = "red";
$colors[1] = "green";
$colors[2] = "yellow";
$colors[3] = "blue";

// 4th way â€” using loop
echo "<ul>";
for ($i = 0; $i < 4; $i++) {
   echo "<li>" . $colors[$i] . "</li>";
}
echo "</ul>";
?>

ğŸ”¸ Associative Arrays

Associative arrays use named keys instead of numeric indexes.

Example
$car = array(
  "brand" => "Ford",
  "model" => "Mustang",
  "year"  => 1964
);

var_dump($car);

ğŸ§¾ Accessing Associative Array Items

Access values using the key name.

$car = array("brand" => "Ford", "model" => "Mustang", "year" => 1964);
echo $car["model"]; // Outputs: Mustang

âœï¸ Changing Array Values

To change a value, use the key name.

$car = array("brand" => "Ford", "model" => "Mustang", "year" => 1964);
$car["year"] = 2024; // Update year
var_dump($car);

ğŸ’¡ Associative Array Example
<?php
$age = array(
  "bill"  => 25,
  "steve" => 28,
  "elon"  => 22
);

// Access each value
echo $age["bill"] . "<br>";
echo $age["steve"] . "<br>";
echo $age["elon"] . "<br>";

// Print the array
echo '<pre>';
print_r($age);
echo '</pre>';

echo '<pre>';
var_dump($age);
echo '</pre>';

// Another way to define an associative array
$age1 = [
  "bill"  => 25,
  "steve" => 28,
  "elon"  => 22
];

echo '<pre>';
print_r($age1);
echo '</pre>';

echo '<pre>';
var_dump($age1);
echo '</pre>';

// Reassign a value
$age["elon"] = 50;

echo '<pre>';
print_r($age);
echo '</pre>';
?>

ğŸ”¢ Arrays with Numeric Keys
$age2 = array(
  100 => 25,
  10  => 28,
  13  => 22
);

echo '<pre>';
print_r($age2);
echo '</pre>';

ğŸ”¤ Arrays with Both Numeric and String Keys
$age3 = array(
  100   => 25,
  "bill" => 28,
  13    => 22
);

echo '<pre>';
var_dump($age3);
echo '</pre>';
?>



ğŸ” Looping Through Arrays in PHP

You can loop through arrays (both indexed and associative) using the foreach loop.
Itâ€™s the easiest and most common way to access every element in an array.

ğŸ§© Loop Through an Indexed Array

Use a foreach loop to print all the values in an indexed array.

ğŸ§  Syntax:
foreach ($array as $value) {
  // Code to execute
}

âœ… Example:
$cars = array("Volvo", "BMW", "Toyota");

foreach ($cars as $x) {
  echo "$x <br>";
}

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Volvo
BMW
Toyota

Another Example:
<?php
$colors = [
  "red",
  "green",
  "blue"
];

foreach ($colors as $value) {
  echo $value . "<br>";
}
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
red
green
blue

ğŸ—ï¸ Loop Through an Associative Array

In associative arrays, each element has a key and a value.
You can loop through both using the foreach loop.

ğŸ§  Syntax:
foreach ($array as $key => $value) {
  // Code using both key and value
}

âœ… Example:
$car = array(
  "brand" => "Ford",
  "model" => "Mustang",
  "year"  => 1964
);

foreach ($car as $x => $y) {
  echo "$x: $y <br>";
}

ğŸ”¹ Output:
brand: Ford
model: Mustang
year: 1964

Another Example:
<?php
$age = [
  "bill"  => 25,
  "steve" => 28,
  "elon"  => 22,
];

foreach ($age as $key => $value) {
  echo "$key = $value <br>";
}
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
bill = 25
steve = 28
elon = 22

ğŸ§± Display Associative Array Inside an HTML List

You can also use foreach to print array elements inside HTML tags.

âœ… Example:
<?php
$age = [
  "bill"  => 25,
  "steve" => 28,
  "elon"  => 22,
];

echo "<ul>";
foreach ($age as $key => $value) {
  echo "<li>$key = $value</li>";
}
echo "</ul>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output (HTML):

bill = 25
steve = 28
elon = 22


ğŸ§© PHP Multidimensional Arrays
A multidimensional array is an array that contains one or more arrays inside it.

ğŸ§  What is a Multidimensional Array?
PHP supports arrays that can be two, three, or even more levels deep â€” though anything beyond three levels is usually difficult to manage.
The dimension of an array represents the number of indices needed to access an element:
| Type                   | Description               | Example Access  |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------- | --------------- |
| 1D (One-dimensional)   | Simple array              | `$arr[0]`       |
| 2D (Two-dimensional)   | Array of arrays           | `$arr[0][1]`    |
| 3D (Three-dimensional) | Array of arrays of arrays | `$arr[0][1][2]` |


ğŸ§± PHP Two-dimensional Arrays
A two-dimensional array is essentially an array of arrays.
You can visualize it like a table â€” with rows and columns.

âœ… Example
<?php
$emp = [
  [1, "Krishana", "Manager", 50000],
  [2, "Salman", "Salesman", 20000],
  [3, "Mohan", "Computer Operator", 12000],
  [4, "Amir", "Driver", 5000]
];

echo "<pre>";
print_r($emp);
echo "</pre>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Array
(
    [0] => Array ( [0] => 1 [1] => Krishana [2] => Manager [3] => 50000 )
    [1] => Array ( [0] => 2 [1] => Salman [2] => Salesman [3] => 20000 )
    [2] => Array ( [0] => 3 [1] => Mohan [2] => Computer Operator [3] => 12000 )
    [3] => Array ( [0] => 4 [1] => Amir [2] => Driver [3] => 5000 )
)


ğŸ¯ Accessing Elements (Row and Column)
To access elements, use two indices â€” [row][column].
echo $emp[0][0] . " "; // 1
echo $emp[0][1] . " "; // Krishana
echo $emp[0][2] . " "; // Manager
echo $emp[0][3] . " "; // 50000


ğŸ” Loop Through a 2D Array Using for Loop
You can use nested for loops â€” one for rows and one for columns.
for ($row = 0; $row < 4; $row++) {
  for ($col = 0; $col < 4; $col++) {
    echo $emp[$row][$col] . " ";
  }
  echo "<br>";
}

ğŸ”¹ Output:
1 Krishana Manager 50000
2 Salman Salesman 20000
3 Mohan Computer Operator 12000
4 Amir Driver 5000


ğŸ”„ Loop Through a 2D Array Using foreach
foreach is simpler and more readable for multidimensional arrays.
foreach ($emp as $v1) {
  foreach ($v1 as $v2) {
    echo $v2 . " ";
  }
  echo "<br>";
}

ğŸ”¹ Output:
1 Krishana Manager 50000
2 Salman Salesman 20000
3 Mohan Computer Operator 12000
4 Amir Driver 5000


ğŸ§® Display Multidimensional Array in an HTML Table
We can make the output more readable by displaying it in a HTML table.
<?php
echo "<table border='2px' cellpadding='5px' cellspacing='0'>";
echo "<tr>
        <th>Emp Id</th>
        <th>Emp Name</th>
        <th>Designation</th>
        <th>Salary</th>
      </tr>";

foreach ($emp as $v1) {
  echo "<tr>";
  foreach ($v1 as $v2) {
    echo "<td>$v2</td>";
  }
  echo "</tr>";
}

echo "</table>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output (HTML Table):
| Emp Id | Emp Name | Designation       | Salary |
| ------ | -------- | ----------------- | ------ |
| 1      | Krishana | Manager           | 50000  |
| 2      | Salman   | Salesman          | 20000  |
| 3      | Mohan    | Computer Operator | 12000  |
| 4      | Amir     | Driver            | 5000   |



ğŸ§© PHP Multidimensional Associative Arrays

A multidimensional associative array is used to store grouped data in the form of keyâ€“value pairs inside multiple levels of arrays.

ğŸ§  What is a Multidimensional Associative Array?

An associative array stores data in keyâ€“value pairs, where the key can be a string or integer.

A multidimensional associative array stores arrays inside another associative array, allowing you to represent structured or related data (like a table of students and their subjects).

ğŸ—ï¸ Example Structure
<?php
$marks = [
  "Krishna" => [
    "physics"    => 85,
    "maths"      => 78,
    "chemistry"  => 89
  ],
  "Salman" => [
    "physics"    => 68,
    "maths"      => 73,
    "chemistry"  => 79
  ],
  "Mohan" => [
    "physics"    => 62,
    "maths"      => 67,
    "chemistry"  => 92
  ]
];

echo "<pre>";
print_r($marks);
echo "</pre>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output (Array Structure)
Array
(
    [Krishna] => Array
        (
            [physics] => 85
            [maths] => 78
            [chemistry] => 89
        )

    [Salman] => Array
        (
            [physics] => 68
            [maths] => 73
            [chemistry] => 79
        )

    [Mohan] => Array
        (
            [physics] => 62
            [maths] => 67
            [chemistry] => 92
        )
)

ğŸ” Loop Through a Multidimensional Associative Array

We can use nested foreach loops â€”
one loop for student names (keys), and another for their subject marks (inner arrays).

âœ… Example:
<?php
foreach ($marks as $student => $subjects) {
  echo $student . ": ";
  
  foreach ($subjects as $marksValue) {
    echo $marksValue . " ";
  }
  
  echo "<br>";
}
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Krishna: 85 78 89
Salman: 68 73 79
Mohan: 62 67 92

ğŸ§® Display in HTML Table

You can represent this data in a tabular format using HTML and PHP loops.

âœ… Example:
<?php
echo "<table border='2px' cellpadding='5px' cellspacing='0'>
  <tr>
    <th>Student Name</th>
    <th>Physics</th>
    <th>Maths</th>
    <th>Chemistry</th>
  </tr>";

foreach ($marks as $student => $subjects) {
  echo "<tr>
          <td>$student</td>";
  
  foreach ($subjects as $marksValue) {
    echo "<td>$marksValue</td>";
  }
  
  echo "</tr>";
}

echo "</table>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output (HTML Table)
| Student Name | Physics | Maths | Chemistry |
| ------------ | ------- | ----- | --------- |
| Krishna      | 85      | 78    | 89        |
| Salman       | 68      | 73    | 79        |
| Mohan        | 62      | 67    | 92        |




ğŸ§© PHP Indexed and Multidimensional Associative Arrays using list()

PHP allows destructuring arrays directly inside a loop using the list() function.
This helps you extract multiple values from each sub-array in a single line, making your code more readable.

ğŸ”¹ 1. Indexed Multidimensional Array with list()
ğŸ§  Concept:

A multidimensional indexed array contains arrays inside another array.
Using list(), you can assign array elements to variables while looping.

âœ… Example:
<?php
/* ----------- Indexed Multidimensional Array ----------- */
$emp = [
  [1, "Krishana", "Manager", 50000],
  [2, "Salman", "Salesman", 20000],
  [3, "Mohan", "Computer Operator", 12000],
  [4, "Amir", "Driver", 5000]
];

foreach ($emp as list($id, $name, $desg, $salary)) {
  echo "$id $name $desg $salary <br>";
}
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
1 Krishana Manager 50000
2 Salman Salesman 20000
3 Mohan Computer Operator 12000
4 Amir Driver 5000

ğŸ§® Displaying Data in an HTML Table

You can also display this array data neatly using a <table>.

<?php
echo "<table border='1px' cellpadding='5px' cellspacing='0'>
  <tr>
    <th>Emp Id</th>
    <th>Emp Name</th>
    <th>Designation</th>
    <th>Salary</th>
  </tr>";

foreach ($emp as list($id, $name, $desg, $salary)) {
  echo "<tr>
          <td>$id</td>
          <td>$name</td>
          <td>$desg</td>
          <td>$salary</td>
        </tr>";
}

echo "</table>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output (HTML Table):
| Emp Id | Emp Name | Designation       | Salary |
| ------ | -------- | ----------------- | ------ |
| 1      | Krishana | Manager           | 50000  |
| 2      | Salman   | Salesman          | 20000  |
| 3      | Mohan    | Computer Operator | 12000  |
| 4      | Amir     | Driver            | 5000   |

ğŸ”¸ 2. Multidimensional Associative Array with list()
ğŸ§  Concept:

In a multidimensional associative array, each inner array contains keyâ€“value pairs.
Using list() with array destructuring (PHP 7.1+), you can assign values by their keys.

âœ… Example:
<?php
/* ----------- Multidimensional Associative Array ----------- */
$emp = [
  ["id" => 1, "name" => "Krishana", "designation" => "Manager", "salary" => 50000],
  ["id" => 2, "name" => "Salman", "designation" => "Salesman", "salary" => 20000],
  ["id" => 3, "name" => "Mohan", "designation" => "Computer Operator", "salary" => 12000],
  ["id" => 4, "name" => "Amir", "designation" => "Driver", "salary" => 5000]
];

foreach ($emp as list("id" => $id, "name" => $name, "designation" => $desg, "salary" => $salary)) {
  echo "Id: $id; Name: $name; Designation: $desg; Salary: $salary<br>";
}
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Id: 1; Name: Krishana; Designation: Manager; Salary: 50000
Id: 2; Name: Salman; Designation: Salesman; Salary: 20000
Id: 3; Name: Mohan; Designation: Computer Operator; Salary: 12000
Id: 4; Name: Amir; Designation: Driver; Salary: 5000



ğŸ§® PHP count() and sizeof() Functions
Both count() and sizeof() are used to count the number of elements in an array.
In PHP, they are identical functions â€” sizeof() is simply an alias of count().

ğŸ”¹ PHP count() Function
ğŸ§  Definition:
The count() function returns the number of elements in an array.
âœ… Example:
<?php
$cars = array("Volvo", "BMW", "Toyota");
echo count($cars);
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
3


âš™ï¸ Syntax:
count(array, mode)

| Parameter | Description                                                                                                                                                                       |
| --------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **array** | (Required) The array to count elements from                                                                                                                                       |
| **mode**  | (Optional) The mode of counting: <br> `0` - Default (does not count elements of multidimensional arrays) <br> `1` - Counts all elements recursively (for multidimensional arrays) |

ğŸ”¸ PHP sizeof() Function
The sizeof() function works exactly the same as count() â€” itâ€™s just another name for it.
âœ… Example:
<?php
$cars = array("Volvo", "BMW", "Toyota");
echo sizeof($cars);
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
3


âš™ï¸ Syntax:
sizeof(array, mode)

| Parameter | Description                                                                    |
| --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **array** | (Required) The array to count elements from                                    |
| **mode**  | (Optional) The mode of counting: <br> `0` - Default <br> `1` - Recursive count |

ğŸ§© Example with Single and Multidimensional Arrays
<?php
$food = array('orange', 'banana', 'apple');

// Mode = 1 (recursive)
echo count($food, 1) . '<br>';

$food1 = array(
  'fruits' => array('orange', 'banana', 'apple'),
  'veggie' => array('carrot', 'collard', 'pea')
);

// Recursive count (mode 1)
echo sizeof($food1, 1) . '<br>';

// Count only fruits
echo sizeof($food1['fruits'], 1) . '<br>';
?>

ğŸ”¹ Explanation:


count($food, 1) â†’ counts all elements in a simple array (3)


sizeof($food1, 1) â†’ counts all elements including nested ones (8)


sizeof($food1['fruits'], 1) â†’ counts only the fruit items (3)



ğŸ” Using count() in a Loop
You can use count() to determine the length of an array for looping.
âœ… Example:
<?php
$food = array('orange', 'banana', 'apple');

$len = count($food);
for ($i = 0; $i < $len; $i++) {
  echo $food[$i] . "<br>";
}
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
orange
banana
apple


ğŸ§® PHP array_count_values() Function
ğŸ§  Definition:
array_count_values() returns an associative array with values as keys and their frequency counts as values.
âœ… Example:
<?php
$food2 = array('orange', 'banana', 'orange', 'apple');

// Count array values
echo "<pre>";
print_r(array_count_values($food2));
echo "</pre>";
?>

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Array
(
    [orange] => 2
    [banana] => 1
    [apple] => 1
)


